I also think you’re hinting at why binary (0/1) or discrete states are useful—not because the world is only binary, but because discrete modes make control and communication simpler.

For example:

* Open / Closed
* Read / Write
* Explore / Exploit
* Zoom In / Zoom Out
* Compress / Expand

Many real systems actually have a continuum between these extremes, but the endpoints serve as useful control states. Then you can add intermediate values if the task benefits from finer control.

In control systems and signal processing, this is a common pattern: define a small set of modes, then modulate continuously within or between them.

